docs.abstract: The New York Times asked the candidates about their plans for housing and homelessness. They back many of the same programs, but are split on national rent control and a renter’s tax credit.
docs.snippet: The New York Times asked the candidates about their plans for housing and homelessness. They back many of the same programs, but are split on national rent control and a renter’s tax credit.
docs.lead_paragraph: More than 550,000 people in the United States are homeless on any given night. More than 18 million spend more than half of their income on housing. And there is no state in which the number of affordable homes matches the number of low-income households.

headline.main: How the Democratic Candidates Would Tackle the Housing Crisis
headline.print_headline: Affordable Homes and Tenant Protections: The Democrats’ Views on Housing

docs.abstract: Arizona’s primary is on Tuesday, and Democrats there are holding onto the idea that they still have control over something: “I want to believe that voting takes away some of the fear.”

docs.lead_paragraph: PHOENIX — Supermarket shelves are barren. Schools are closing across the country. But in Arizona, many Democrats are hoping that voting in the presidential primary provides a slice of normalcy at a time that is anything but normal.

headline.main: In Arizona, Voting During a Pandemic Is a Way to Feel Normal
headline.print_headline: Democrats Plan to Vote As Source of Comfort:  ‘What Is Normal Now?’

docs.abstract: Joe Biden swept Arizona, Florida and Illinois and Bernie Sanders continued to lose ground in the Democratic primary’s delegate count.
docs.snippet: Joe Biden swept Arizona, Florida and Illinois and Bernie Sanders continued to lose ground in the Democratic primary’s delegate count.
docs.lead_paragraph: Joseph R. Biden Jr. swept the three states that voted Tuesday: Florida, Illinois and Arizona. Bernie Sanders lost ground badly in the delegate count. And the coronavirus pandemic continued to wreak havoc on the most basic facets of American life, threatening to disrupt if not derail the remaining primary calendar.

headline.print_headline: 4 Takeaways From a Rout That Tightens Biden’s Grip

docs.lead_paragraph: BURLINGTON, Vt. — Senator Bernie Sanders has canceled a planned rally in Jackson, Miss., and will instead travel to Michigan on Friday, a striking indication that his presidential campaign is shifting its focus to the Midwest and largely ceding another Southern state to former Vice President Joseph R. Biden Jr., according to people familiar with the plans.
